May 15, 2022



Hello Dmitri,



I thought you might enjoy highlights from our recent report (HOB - A Gravit=
ational Pull), looking at recent macroeconomic signals (eg: Inflation, Inte=
rest Rates, Hightend Recession Risk, etc...) and what we believe these sign=
als mean, their impact on real estate and what strategies can be derived fr=
om these.



Last Year (one for the record books)



*         Real estate emerged from Covid with strong demand and few supply =
concerns

*         All-time high rent increases

*         Surging equity capital flows

*         Low interest rates and accommodative financing



This Year



*         Suddenly feeling the weight of significantly higher borrowing cos=
ts.

o   More deals are getting re-traded.

o   Widening bid-ask spreads portends a slowdown in transaction volume.

*         Demand for commercial real estate assets has been nearly insatiab=
le.

o   Investors are awash in a sea of capital.

o   Closed-end fundraising by private equity funds approximated a record-hi=
gh.

*         Heightened recession risk.

*         Consternation over inflation has grown considerably in recent mon=
ths.

*         Annual cost of homeownership for the median home in the top-50 la=
rgest metros has increased by an average ~20%.


The corporate bond and listed REIT signals are flashing red.  The surge in =
interest rates has brought commercial real estate borrowing costs to a leve=
l above cap rates for the first time since the lead-up to the Global Financ=
ial Crisis.



[Chart, waterfall chart  Description automatically generated]



The future direction of property prices is highly uncertain, but the gravit=
ational pull is growing stronger. On a relative basis, real estate is poise=
d to underperform corporate bonds. And an absolute decline in property pric=
es in the 0-10% range is the most likely, but not necessarily odds-on, scen=
ario over the balance of the year.



[Chart, line chart  Description automatically generated]



But this is just one of many insight reports we produce to help guide inves=
tments and investment strategy.  For example:



*         Post Covid San Francisco

o   This report puts San Francisco's office market during Covid in context =
and examines the potential future for the beleaguered market

*         Office Insights - Case for Quality

o   A review of Green Street's recent analysis suggests Class A office buil=
dings are better positioned than Class B

*         WFH Reassessing

o   With two years in the rear-view mirror, several conclusions on the impa=
ct of WFH on the office sector can be drawn.

*         NYC Local Emissions

o   Monitoring markets for regulatory changes, particularly on 'green' issu=
es, remains a key focus to spot potential NOI disruptions.



Economic Sensitivity



Pick your sector wisely.



[Chart, scatter chart  Description automatically generated]



[Timeline  Description automatically generated with medium confidence]



ESG/Net Zero



[Chart, bubble chart  Description automatically generated]





Let me know if this catches your interest and I would be happy to give you =
a quick tour of our research library so you can get a better sense of our r=
esearch and content.



Best Regards,


Matt Souter
